<paragraph id="900F36E8FFCDBA38FF0E716853B201A9" blockId="1.[151,1436,1471,2014]" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCDBA38FF0E7168575A0164" bold="true" box="[199,363,1887,1910]" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Biogeography.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCDBA38FEBB7169547F0164" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[370,590,1886,1910]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCDBA38FEBB7169547F0164" box="[370,590,1886,1910]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Sphallopterus batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described from two localities in northern 
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCDBA38FB7D716852C40164" box="[1204,1269,1887,1910]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(state of 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCDBA38FA95716853A00164" box="[1372,1425,1887,1910]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Pará</collectingRegion>
): Óbidos (
<typeStatus id="4F0B884AFFCDBA38FF3071B55768018B" box="[249,345,1922,1945]" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">holotype</typeStatus>
) and Mocajuba (
<typeStatus id="4F0B884AFFCDBA38FDED71B554B7018B" box="[548,646,1922,1945]" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">paratype</typeStatus>
). According to recent biogeographical scheme of Neotropical region (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCDBA38FF577193570D01A9" author="Morrone" box="[158,316,1956,1979]" pageId="1" pageNumber="263" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2017) Neotropical Biogeography: regionalization and evolution. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 282 pp." type="book" year="2017">Morrone 2017</bibRefCitation>
), Óbidos is located in 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCDBA38FDE3719354B701A9" box="[554,646,1956,1979]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Roraima</collectingRegion>
biogeographic province and Mocajuba in 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCDBA38FB807193524901A9" box="[1097,1144,1956,1979]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Pará</collectingRegion>
biogeographic province.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8AA6563FFCDBA3BFF0E71F055900705" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="264" pageId="1" pageNumber="263" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="900F36E8FFCDBA3BFF0E71F055900705" blockId="1.[151,1436,1471,2014]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,152,279]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="264" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">
With the new records the individual track obtained (
<figureCitation id="088B2A6DFFCDBA38FD2471F0551D01CC" box="[749,812,1991,2014]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,244,1205,1227]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,195,1180]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1437,191,1184]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Individual trackof Sphallopterus batesi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1145629/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) links the known area of distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCDBA38FB1E71F0530001CC" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[1239,1329,1990,2014]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCDBA38FB1E71F0530001CC" box="[1239,1329,1990,2014]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">S. batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCDBA38FAF771F053AA01CC" box="[1342,1435,1991,2014]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="1" pageNumber="263">Roraima</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCEBA3BFF0F76AF56C406BD" box="[198,245,152,175]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Pará</collectingRegion>
biogeographic provinces) with the biogeographic provinces of Madeira (where Jirau in 
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCEBA3BFB7A76AF52C506BD" box="[1203,1268,152,175]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Brazil</collectingCountry>
is located) and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCEBA3BFF5E768D573006C3" box="[151,257,186,209]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
, where the new record of 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCEBA3BFDDC768D546906C3" box="[533,600,186,209]" country="Bolivia" name="Pando" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Pando</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCEBA3BFDAF768D548606C3" box="[614,695,186,209]" name="Bolivia" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
) is located. The four biogeographic provinces belong to the Brazilian subregion of the Neotropical region, although 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCEBA3BFD4476EA54D806E6" box="[653,745,221,244]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Roraima</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCEBA3BFCD676EA557F06E6" box="[799,846,221,244]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Pará</collectingRegion>
belong to the Boreal Brazilian dominion and Madeira and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCEBA3BFF0D7737571D0705" box="[196,300,256,279]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="2" pageNumber="264">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
belongs to the South Brazilian dominion (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCEBA3BFD39773755A70705" author="Morrone" box="[752,918,256,279]" pageId="2" pageNumber="264" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2017) Neotropical Biogeography: regionalization and evolution. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 282 pp." type="book" year="2017">Morrone, 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
