<subSection id="F93F2F03FFCFBA3DFF5E732B551106C3" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="266" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" type="discussion">
<subSubSection id="D8AA6563FFCFBA3AFF5E732B537303AF" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="900F36E8FFCFBA3AFF5E732B572A0324" blockId="3.[151,1436,1308,2024]" box="[151,283,1308,1334]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
<heading id="CB478184FFCFBA3AFF5E732B572A0324" bold="true" box="[151,283,1308,1334]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" reason="1">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFF5E732B572A0324" bold="true" box="[151,283,1308,1334]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Discussion</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="900F36E8FFCFBA3AFF5E7309537303AF" blockId="3.[151,1436,1308,2024]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
Examination of the female 
<typeStatus id="4F0B884AFFCFBA3AFE097309542C0347" box="[448,541,1342,1365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="088B2A6DFFCFBA3AFDE47309545F0347" box="[557,622,1342,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1862,1884]" captionTargetBox="[353,1237,335,1820]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[340,1247,333,1841]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype (female) of Sphallopterus batesi, dorsal view. MNRJ Museu Nacional, Universidade Federal do Rio Janeiro. Scale bar:11.0 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1145627/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) shows that the most significant difference between female and male of 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFA41730956E6036A" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFA41730956E6036A" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">S. batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the shorter antennae in female, reaching elytral apex at about basal quarter of antennomere XI (
<typeStatus id="4F0B884AFFCFBA3AFAE4735653A1036A" box="[1325,1424,1377,1400]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">holotype</typeStatus>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFEE473B454720388" author="Martins" box="[301,579,1411,1434]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Monne, M. A. (2005) Tribo Cerambycini. In: Martins, U. R. (Ed.), Cerambycidae Sul-americanos (Coleoptera). Taxonomia. Vol. 5. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Sao Paulo, pp. 207 - 209." type="book" year="2005">Martins &amp; Monné (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFD8673B4549D0388" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[591,684,1410,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFD8673B4549D0388" box="[591,684,1410,1434]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">S. batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to species of 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFC7B73B552F80388" authority="Fragoso, 1981" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1981" box="[946,1225,1410,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Xestiodion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFC7B73B552150388" box="[946,1060,1410,1434]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Xestiodion</emphasis>
Fragoso, 1981
</taxonomicName>
, due to femora and tibiae bicolorous, but 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFEB67392542203AF" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[383,531,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFEB67392542203AF" box="[383,531,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Sphallopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFCFF7392559903AF" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1981" box="[822,936,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Xestiodion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFCFF7392559903AF" box="[822,936,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Xestiodion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the reddish and unicolorous elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8AA6563FFCFBA3DFF0E73FE551106C3" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="266" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="900F36E8FFCFBA3AFF0E73FE57CA00E7" blockId="3.[151,1436,1308,2024]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFF0E73FE575503F2" bold="true" box="[199,356,1481,1504]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Biogeography</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFEBE73FF546903F2" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[375,600,1480,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFEBE73FF546903F2" box="[375,600,1480,1504]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Sphallopterus batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was previously reported as endemic to 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFBE273FE52B603F2" box="[1067,1159,1481,1504]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Roraima</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFB0E73FE52C703F2" box="[1223,1270,1481,1504]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Pará</collectingRegion>
biogeographic provinces in 
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCFBA3AFED673DC57510010" box="[287,352,1515,1538]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Boreal Brazilian dominion), and is now additionally known from Madeira biogeographic province in 
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCFBA3AFF5E703956E90037" box="[151,216,1550,1573]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFEC2703957420037" box="[267,371,1550,1573]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
biogeographic province in 
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCFBA3AFD5E703954D40037" box="[663,741,1550,1573]" name="Bolivia" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(South Brazilian dominion), this last area constitutes the western limit of the distribution of the species. The Brazilian subregion comprises central and southern 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFB4F700652EB005A" box="[1158,1242,1585,1608]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
<collectingCountry id="E8A77678FFCFBA3AFB4F700652EB005A" box="[1158,1242,1585,1608]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, Central America, and northwestern South America (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFDD4706454FB0078" author="Morrone" box="[541,714,1619,1642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2014) Biogeographical regionalisation of the Neotropical region. Zootaxa, 3782 (1), 1 - 110. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3782.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">Morrone, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The dominions of the Brazilian subregion split following the sequence (Boreal Brazilian [South Brazilian (Pacific, Mesoamerican)]), and the vicariance between the Boreal Brazilian dominion (the 
<typeStatus id="4F0B884AFFCFBA3AFEFA70AE575000A2" box="[307,353,1689,1712]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">type</typeStatus>
area of 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFCFBA3AFE7E70AF54A000A2" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[439,657,1688,1712]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFE7E70AF54A000A2" box="[439,657,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Sphallopterus batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the remaining areas (specially the South Brazilian dominion, where the new records of the species are located) can be associated with the Romeral Fault Zone and/or the final uplift of the northern Andes (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFE8370E957C100E7" author="Morrone" box="[330,496,1758,1781]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2017) Neotropical Biogeography: regionalization and evolution. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 282 pp." type="book" year="2017">Morrone, 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="900F36E8FFCFBA3DFF0E7136551106C3" blockId="3.[151,1436,1308,2024]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1435,152,209]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="266" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
The biogeographic relationship between 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFD4B713654EF010A" box="[642,734,1793,1816]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Roraima</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFCDF71365574010A" box="[790,837,1793,1816]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Pará</collectingRegion>
biogeographic provinces, the first basically formed by savannas and gallery forests and the second by moist forests and flooded grasslands, was not considered previously (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFF577171570C014F" author="Morrone" box="[158,317,1862,1885]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2017) Neotropical Biogeography: regionalization and evolution. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 282 pp." type="book" year="2017">Morrone 2017</bibRefCitation>
); the individual track obtained in this work is the first contribution linking both biogeographic provinces. The 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFF02715E56CB0192" box="[203,250,1897,1920]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Pará</collectingRegion>
province was related previously with 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFD61715E55210192" box="[680,784,1897,1920]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
province with biogeographic analysis based on avian taxa (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFF5771BC576601B0" author="Bates" box="[158,343,1930,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Bates, J. M., Hackett, S. J. &amp; Cracraft, J. (1998) &quot; Area-relationships in the Neotropical lowlands: an hypothesis based on raw distributions of Passerine birds. &quot; Journal of Biogeography, 25, 783 - 793. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1365 - 2699.1998.2540783. x" type="journal article" year="1998">
Bates 
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFCFBA3AFF2B71BC572901B0" box="[226,280,1930,1954]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">et al.</emphasis>
1998
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFEAA71BC57DD01B0" author="Borges" box="[355,492,1931,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Borges, S. H. (2007) Analise biogeografica da avifauna da regiao oeste do baixo Rio Negro, Amazonia brasileira. Revista Brasileira de Zoologia, 24, 919 - 940. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0101 - 81752007000400008" type="journal article" year="2007">Borges 2007</bibRefCitation>
) and primate species (
<bibRefCitation id="F4214B19FFCFBA3AFD1571BC559C01B0" author="Silva" box="[732,941,1931,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refString="Silva, J. M. C. &amp; Oren, D. C. (1996) Application of parsimony analysis of endemicity in Amazonian biogeography: An example with primates. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 59, 427 - 437. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1095 - 8312.1996. tb 01475. x" type="journal article" year="1996">Silva &amp; Oren 1996</bibRefCitation>
). This last work also relates the 
<collectingRegion id="5274F80AFFCFBA3AFAC171BC530601B0" box="[1288,1335,1931,1954]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Pará</collectingRegion>
province with Madeira province. Therefore, our work is the first study linking all these biogeographic provinces using an insect species. All biogeographic provinces connected with the individual track share similar habitats: a wide range of forest 
<typeStatus id="4F0B884AFFC8BA3DFF5E76AF56FE06BD" box="[151,207,152,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="266">types</typeStatus>
which includes a mosaic of flooded grasslands and gallery forests, so it is probably that the gallery forests along rivers would be the preferred habitat of 
<taxonomicName id="57B04D6BFFC8BA3DFDF6768E552806C3" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[575,793,185,209]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sphallopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis id="A2C4EAFAFFC8BA3DFDF6768E552806C3" box="[575,793,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="266">Sphallopterus batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
